'''Amaral''' is a [[Impact crater|crater]] on the [[planet]] [[Mercury (planet)|Mercury]]. With its smooth floor, surrounding [[ejecta]], and small [[secondary crater]]s, it appears noticeably younger than the heavily cratered surface around it. Along with a smooth crater floor, Amaral also has a central peak. Bright material on this peak is of particular interest as it appears to have an unusual color. In color-enhanced images, the central peak of Amaral appears as a bright [[blue]] color in striking contrast to the otherwise [[Orange (colour)|orange]] tones of surface material nearby. The different color of the central peak likely indicates rocks with different [[chemical composition]] from those on the neighboring surface.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://messenger.jhuapl.edu/gallery/sciencePhotos/image.php?page=1&gallery_id=2&image_id=286 |title=messenger.jhuapl.edu. |access-date=2009-06-14 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150923221725/http://messenger.jhuapl.edu/gallery/sciencePhotos/image.php?page=1&gallery_id=2&image_id=286 |archive-date=2015-09-23 |dead-url=yes |df= }}</ref>

