A '''data science competition platform''' is used by businesses to host [[data science]] challenges that are hard to solve for one group. Historically, [[crowdsourcing]] challenges have been known to solve very complex problems.<ref>{{cite journal|url=https://www.nature.com/articles/nrg.2016.69|title=Crowdsourcing biomedical research: leveraging communities as innovation engines|first1=Julio|last1=Saez-Rodriguez|first2=James C.|last2=Costello|first3=Stephen H.|last3=Friend|first4=Michael R.|last4=Kellen|first5=Lara|last5=Mangravite|first6=Pablo|last6=Meyer|first7=Thea|last7=Norman|first8=Gustavo|last8=Stolovitzky|publisher=|journal=Nature Reviews Genetics|volume=17|issue=8|pages=470–486|doi=10.1038/nrg.2016.69}}</ref> The [[Netflix Prize]] is one such competition. Since then there have been several platforms developed on the idea of data science competitions. Research has been completed on how competition can improve research performance. 

Examples of data science competition platforms include [[Kaggle]], [[InnoCentive]], and Alibaba Tianchi.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tianchi.aliyun.com/index.htm|title=Tianchi: Platform of Crowd Intelligence|website=tianchi.aliyun.com}}</ref> [[Alibaba]]'s competition platform which was used in [[SIGKDD|KDD]] 2017.

