'''François Pierre Nicholas Gillet de Laumont''' (28 May 1747 – 1 June 1834) was a [[France|French]] [[mineralogist]].

He was born in [[Paris]], educated at a military school and served in the army from 1772 to 1784, when he was appointed inspector of mines. His attention in his leisure time was wholly given to [[mineralogy]], and he assisted in organizing the new [[Mines ParisTech|École des Mines]] in Paris. 

He was author of numerous mineralogical papers in the "''Journal et Annales des Mines''". The mineral [[laumontite]], which Laumont discovered in the mines of [[Huelgoat]], was named after him by [[René Just Haüy]].<ref name=HH>[https://books.google.com/books?id=ElcEAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA75&lpg=PA75&dq=%22Gillet+de+Laumont%22+1747&source=bl&ots=QeUgTp-zKV&sig=AeljHpP9aDLurO3UsWLzpyRJFxU&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjXns-VjfDJAhUGdh4KHbpjBMYQ6AEISDAH#v=onepage&q=%22Gillet%20de%20Laumont%22%201747&f=false Records of General Science, Volume 2] edited by [[Robert Dundas Thomson]], Thomas Thomson</ref> After the death of [[Jean-Baptiste L. Romé de l'Isle]] in 1790, Laumont purchased his large collection of minerals and crystals.<ref>[http://www.yourmineralcollection.com/Rome.htm Romè de l'Isle] Your Mineral Collection - Mineral Books</ref>

During his career, he was awarded with the [[Order of the Reunion|Ordre de la Réunion]] (1813), the [[Légion d'honneur]] (1815) and the [[Ordre de Saint-Michel]] (1819).<ref name=HH/> He died in Paris in 1834.

