Dole, Stephen H. <mark>Habitable</mark> <mark>planets</mark> for <mark>man</mark> [by] Stephen Dole. [1st ed.]Santa Monica, Calif., Rand Corp., 1964. xi, 158 p. illus. 23 cm. AS36 .R3 R-414 </ref>]] '''''Habitable Planets For Man''''' is a work by [[Stephen Dole]], first edition published by Blaisdell Publishing Company, A division of Ginn and Company, copyright 1964 by The [[RAND Corporation]]. Originally 158 pages, it was republished in a posthumous second edition in 2007, as ''Planets for Man''.<ref>{{cite book |author=Stephen H. Dole |authorlink=Stephen Dole |title = Habitable Planets for Man |url=https://books.google.com/books/about/Habitable_planets_for_man.html?id=-z9AAAAAIAAJ |edition=2nd |location=New York |publisher=American Elsevier |year=1970 }}</ref> The revised edition, 174-page book, contains a detailed scientific study on the nature of worlds that may support life in the universe, the probability of their existence, and ways of finding them,<ref name="http://blogs.scientificamerican.com">{{cite web|url=http://blogs.scientificamerican.com/life-unbounded/2011/09/13/the-habitable-planets/ |author=Caleb A. Scharf | title = The Habitable Planets | publisher=Life Unbounded, ''[[Scientific American]]'' |date=September 13, 2011 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title = Planet Life |publisher=Science Notes, ''[[The New York Times]]'' |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1964/07/12/science-notes-planet-life.html |date=July 12, 1964}}</ref> including assessments of 14 stars within 22 [[light year]]s with a relatively high probability of having [[habitable planet]]s (a collective probability of 43%).<ref>{{cite journal |author=William C. Saslaw |title=Review: ''Habitable Planets for Man'' by Stephen H. Dole |work=American Scientist |volume=52 |issue=4 |date=December 1964 |jstor=27839216 |pages=466A&ndash;477A }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |author=Joe W. Tyson |title=Review: ''Habitable Planets for Man'' by Stephen H. Dole |work=The Quarterly Review of Biology |volume=40 |issue=2 |date=June 1965 |jstor=2819795 |page=229 |doi=10.1086/404644}}</ref> Writing in a ''[[Scientific American]]'' blog in 2011, Caleb Scharf called it "extraordinarily detailed and prescient".<ref name="http://blogs.scientificamerican.com"/>
