{{Update|inaccurate=yes|date=August 2016}} The following is a '''list of [[Solar variation|solar cycle]]s''' (sometimes called [[sunspot]] cycles), tracked since 1755 following the original numbering proposed by Rudolf Wolf in the mid-19th century<ref name="Kane">Kane, R.P. (2002). "[http://www.springerlink.com/content/qtq52nl8vtq7w2t6/ Some Implications Using the Group Sunspot Number Reconstruction]". ''Solar Physics'' '''205(2)''', 383-401.</ref><ref>"[http://www.spacetoday.org/SolSys/Sun/Sunspots.html Did You Say the Sun Has Spots?]". ''Space Today Online''.</ref> The source data are the revised International Sunspot Numbers (ISN v2.0), as available at SILSO.<ref>{{cite web|title=Sunspot numbers|url=http://www.sidc.be/silso/datafiles|website=WDC-SILSO|publisher=Royal Observatory of Belgium|accessdate=19 May 2017}}</ref> Sunspot number counts exist since 1610<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Hathaway,|first1=D.|title=The solar cycle|journal=Living Reviews in Solar Physics|date=2015|volume=12|page=4|doi=10.1007/lrsp-2015-4|arxiv=1502.07020|bibcode=2015LRSP...12....4H}}</ref> but the cycle numbering is not well defined during the [[Maunder minimum]].<ref>{{cite web|title=The Maunder minimum|url=https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Maunder_Minimum}}</ref>{{Better source|reason=per WP:CIRCULAR|date=November 2017}} It was proposed that one cycle might have been lost in the late 18th century,<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Usoskin|first1=et al.|title=A solar cycle lost in 1793-1800: Early sunspot observations resolve the old mystery|journal=Astrophys. J. Lett.|volume=700|page=L154|doi=10.1088/0004-637X/700/2/L154|arxiv=0907.0063|bibcode=2009ApJ...700L.154U}}</ref> but this still remains not fully confirmed.
The smoothing was done using the traditional SIDC smoothing formula.<ref>{{cite web|title=SIDC smoothing formula|url=http://www.sidc.be/silso/node/52|website=WDC-SILSO|publisher=Royal Observatory of Belgium|accessdate=19 May 2017}}</ref> Other smoothing formulas exist, and they usually give slightly different values for the amplitude and timings of the solar cycles. An example is the Meeus smoothing formula,<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Meeus|first1=J.|title=Une formule d'adoucissement pour l'activité solaire|journal=Ciel et Terre|date=1958|volume=74|page=445|bibcode=1958C&T....74..445M}}</ref> with related solar cycles characteristics available in this STCE news item.<ref>{{cite web|title=The solar cycle's new clothes|url=http://www.stce.be/news/312/welcome.html|website=STCE|publisher=Royal Observatory of Belgium|accessdate=8 July 2015}}</ref>
In the table below, the number of spotless days is the number between the maximum of the previous solar cycle and the maximum of the new solar cycle. As an example, there were 817 spotless days during the transit from solar cycle 23 to solar cycle 24.
