The '''nucleus incertus''' is a region of the rodent pontine [[brainstem]] just ventral to the 4th [[ventricle (brain)|ventricle]].<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Goto|first1=M|last2=Swanson|first2=LW|last3=Canteras|first3=NS|title=Connections of the nucleus incertus.|journal=The Journal of Comparative Neurology|date=Sep 10, 2001|volume=438|issue=1|pages=86–122|pmid=11503154|doi=10.1002/cne.1303}}</ref>

The nucleus incertus has a bilateral structure which sits near the brainstem, and is often also called 'nucleus O'. It consists of mostly ascending [[GABAergic]] [[projection neuron]]s and [[glutamatergic]] neurons<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Cervera-Ferri|first1=A|last2=Rahmani|first2=Y|last3=Martínez-Bellver|first3=S|last4=Teruel-Martí|first4=V|last5=Martínez-Ricós|first5=J|title=Glutamatergic projection from the nucleus incertus to the septohippocampal system.|journal=Neuroscience Letters|date=May 31, 2012|volume=517|issue=2|pages=71–6|pmid=22521581|doi=10.1016/j.neulet.2012.04.014}}</ref> which innervate a broad range of [[forebrain]] regions involved in behavioural activation and the [[stress response|response to stress]].<ref>{{cite journal|last=Ryan|first=Phil|author2=Ma S |author3=Olucha-Bordonau FE |author4=Gundlach AL |title=Nucleus incertus--an emerging modulatory role in arousal, stress and memory|journal=Neuroscience & Biobehavioral Reviews|date=May 2011|volume=35|issue=6|pages=1326–41|doi=10.1016/j.neubiorev.2011.02.004}}</ref>

This tegmental nucleus is part of the theta network. The nucleus incertus is a relay from the reticularis pontis oralis nucleus to the septo-hippocampal system.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Teruel-Martí|first1=V|last2=Cervera-Ferri|first2=A|last3=Nuñez|first3=A|last4=Valverde-Navarro|first4=AA|last5=Olucha-Bordonau|first5=FE|last6=Ruiz-Torner|first6=A|title=Anatomical evidence for a ponto-septal pathway via the nucleus incertus in the rat.|journal=Brain Research|date=Jul 7, 2008|volume=1218|pages=87–96|pmid=18514169|doi=10.1016/j.brainres.2008.04.022}}</ref> The stimulation of the nucleus incertus activates the hippocampal theta rhythm and either its lesion or inhibition suppress the theta oscillation induced by brainstem stimulation.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Nuñez|first1=A|last2=Cervera-Ferri|first2=A|last3=Olucha-Bordonau|first3=F|last4=Ruiz-Torner|first4=A|last5=Teruel|first5=V|title=Nucleus incertus contribution to hippocampal theta rhythm generation.|journal=The European Journal of Neuroscience|date=May 2006|volume=23|issue=10|pages=2731–8|pmid=16817876|doi=10.1111/j.1460-9568.2006.04797.x}}</ref> The nucleus incertus itself presents theta oscillations coupled to the hippocampal theta rhythm.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Cervera-Ferri|first1=A|last2=Guerrero-Martínez|first2=J|last3=Bataller-Mompeán|first3=M|last4=Taberner-Cortes|first4=A|last5=Martínez-Ricós|first5=J|last6=Ruiz-Torner|first6=A|last7=Teruel-Martí|first7=V|title=Theta synchronization between the hippocampus and the nucleus incertus in urethane-anesthetized rats.|journal=Experimental Brain Research|date=Jun 2011|volume=211|issue=2|pages=177–92|pmid=21479657|doi=10.1007/s00221-011-2666-3}}</ref>

