{{Brown-dwarf-stub}}

[[File:Waga 01.jpg|upright 0.6|thumb|A waga near [[Konso]], Ethiopia]]
A '''waga''', also known as a '''waka''' or '''waaka''', is a type of memorial statue carved from wood in southern [[Ethiopia]].  Modern wagas or mini-wagas may also be carved specifically for sale to tourists, in which case the rod-shaped ''kallaccas'' on their heads are often exaggerated into phallic shapes.<ref>Amborn, Hermann.  [http://portal.svt.ntnu.no/sites/ices16/Proceedings/Volume%202/Hermann%20Amborn-%20The%20Phallsification%20of%20the%20Kalla%C4%8D%C4%8Da.pdf "The Phallsification of the Kallacca: or, Why Sometimes a Cigar is a Cigar"], Proceedings of the 16th International Conference of Ethiopian Studies p. 404, 2009.</ref>

