[[Category:Anthropology]]

{{anthropology-stub}}

'''Yhprum's law''' is the opposite of [[Murphy's law]].
The simple formula of Yhprum's law is: "Everything that can work, will work."
Another formulation of the law due to [[Richard Zeckhauser]], a professor for [[political economy]] at [[Harvard University]] states: "Sometimes systems that should not work, work nevertheless."
Resnick ''et al''. (2006) used this law to describe how intensive and seemingly [[altruistic]] participation by giving ranking is observed in the [[eBay]] system.<ref name=Resnick06>{{cite journal|last=Resnick|first=Paul|author2=Zeckhauser, Richard |author3=Swanson, John |author4= Lockwood, Kate |title=The value of reputation on eBay: A controlled experiment|journal=Experimental Economics|date=June 2006|volume=9|issue=2|pages=79–101|doi=10.1007/s10683-006-4309-2|url=http://www.hks.harvard.edu/fs/rzeckhau/postcards.pdf}}</ref>
